{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f34b0725-8ff0-4ce7-9014-0245c0f83885","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can give you the guidance you need. To publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool**, add these properties to your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n  <PackageOutputPath>./nupkg</PackageOutputPath>\n\n  <!-- Required NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server using stdio transport.</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key properties:**\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the project as a dotnet tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users will run |\n| `OutputType` | Must be `Exe` (should already be set) |\n\n**Publish steps:**\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push ./nupkg/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Users install & run with:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server  # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the minimum. You don't need to change your stdio transport code — `PackAsTool` handles the rest.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"64205ba9-1ab0-41f1-a19d-76eceb743a93","outputTokens":469,"requestId":"D037:301399:1589929:1809224:6A06743B"},"id":"d44fe676-f385-45f3-82e8-a963a6270c6d","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:17:56.953Z","parentId":"3f3a8de2-bc06-45ec-8d88-06242b07ac2e"}
